I had heard about this place through friends and decided to get brunch since I was in the city. It started with an hour n half wait for a table but I was entertained for the duration by the sheer number of people who were waiting with me. The food is AMAZING! Brenda's is worth checking out if you're in the Civic Center/Tenderloin area. I don't think it quite lives up to its intense hype, but check it out and decide for yourself. If you are planning on coming here for their chicken I would not recommend it! As one of the main courses, BFC, it was not good.

Yay! Finally got to try this place and had my beignet cravings satisfied! I was afraid to end the day with food coma so I ordered 1 cinnamon apple beignet ($2) 1 crawfish beignet ($3) 1 cheddar grits ($3.25) It was the perfect amount for me! (as I chuckle to myself for not having to spend $20 on lunch). The crawfish beignet was just so amazing, the amount cheese oozing out was just right, along with the hot filling of savory crawfish bits and the generous paprika on top -- minus any greasy feeling you would get with beignets anywhere else... I was eating and involuntarily nodding my head in approval the whole time. The cinnamon apple beignet filling was a little dry for me, but I did like how they spiced it (and it added a bit of sweetness to my meal, I liked that). I used the peaches preserves on the table to go with this beignet. Lastly, the cheddar grits! I finally understood what comfort food means. So. Good. If you're chinese, this is like a creamier version of 小米粥, a little more savory and I think the cheddar complements it very well. all in all-- a great experience! definitely will be coming back for other things! (wish parking wasn't such a pain) Tip: once you get in, write your name on the whiteboard towards your right hand side.

I'm going against the majority here to describe my extremely subpar experience at Brenda's. We got here around 9:20 am on a Saturday morning and there was already a long list of names waiting to be seated. I didn't specifically ask for the wait time because I knew I wanted to try this place regardless but a party of 2 that came in shortly after us was told that it would be 15-20 minutes. We were also a party of 2, and we ended up waiting over 40 minutes for a table. They move EXTREMELY SLOW. So many empty tables were open for long periods of time and they wouldn't seat people - I have no idea why. A restaurant as popular as Brenda's should have turnover pretty nailed down at this point but it was painstakingly slow. After 10 am, the wait was looking to be over 2 hours with a huge crowd outside the restaurant. The food was really just ok and way over hyped. We tried the beignet flight - good, but nothing amazing. I've definitely had better beignets. The apple one was most disappointing - both the filling and bread were so dry. Crawfish beignets were unique but I wouldn't come back here just for those. We also got the gumbo which was light and tasty. It has a lot of okra in it so make sure you like okra if you're planning on getting this. The last thing we ordered was the pulled pork benedict special which was a huge mistake. Pulled pork was overly salted to the point where it was almost inedible. The biscuit was crumbly and hard and the hollandaise just added unnecessary creamy cheesiness to an already heavy dish. I rarely send dishes back but I had to tell the waitress that I couldn't eat this at all. She was kind enough to take it off the bill without any issue. I'm adding one star for making that an easy process for me. Based on the extremely long wait times and the selection of menu items I've tried, I won't be returning to this spot.

I have been wanting to try this place forever but there is ALWAYS a long wait, so one Monday when we called around 2pm we were ecstatic to hear that there was NO WAIT at all! It might be a little difficult to find, there is not a huge sign, but it is right next door to the coffee shop that says that they serve food from Brenda's. I really wanted to try the benedicts but they only serve those on the weekends for brunch. We opted for the crawfish beignets, jambalaya (special), and BFC (their version of fried chicken). My fiance is a huge fan of crawfish and he thought the crawfish itself was delicious. They were super flavorful, not super spicy. We both agreed the breading for the beignet was a big plain and a bit much, but getting to the inside with the crawfish made it all worth it. It was definitely worth it cause you get three decently sized beignets! The jambalaya was surprisingly not as spicy as other places, which is good for me because I cannot handle spicy. For you spicy lovers out there you made need to add more fire to it. It was solid, definitely something to get again, and it comes with a salad. The BFC is honestly the BEST part of the meal. It was just right amount of crispiness and super moist on the inside. You get two pretty big pieces too, which is perfect for sharing for you to eat all yourself. If you come to Brenda's you MUST get the fried chicken. I can't wait to come back to try the benedicts, especially the fried chicken benedicts!

Lend me your ear (ok, eyes) for a second and I'll tell you a tale of one of the top (if not THE top) brunch experiences I've had in San Francisco... It was a brisk (what day in SF isn't, really?), Sunday afternoon and three sisters had a hankering for brunch (which is totally the new happy hour). Armed with the Yelp app, and some insider info, they made their way to the Tenderloin. Yes, the TL, as the locals call it. Now, the TL gets a bad rap, but most of it is deserved, however there are some real diamonds in its rough if you're willing to put on your prostitute and druggie repellant and make the trek there. Brenda's already had a wait (which is a given since they serve a flight of beignets), among other phenomenal dishes. Instead of wallowing in "why didn't we get up earlier" pity, we walked over to Phillz for a little pre-brunch beverage and snack while we waited. We prob did wait close to an hour but we found a pocket of sunshine to stand in and sipped on our warm beverages so it wasn't completely unbearable. They have a specials board outside that makes you drool in anticipation of what will soon be plated in front of you, and on this particular day I had decided on the pulled pork eggs benedict. It was gorgeously designed with a huge, fluffy poached egg with a silky stream of just enough yolk to complement the pulled pork on the creamy biscuit. Seriously, a whopper, and as if that wasn't enough, it came with some killer bfast potatoes/hash. I also ordered a Creole Bloody Mary that wasn't really as exciting as it sounds, but the dish was so spot on that the drink really wouldn't have held a candle to it any way. Sadly we didn't order the beignets, as our eyes were bigger than our hunger pains, but that just means a visit to Brenda's will be in my SF future. The end.

    Management: please consider incorporating technology to text patrons when our tables are ready. There are always masses of people waiting on the sidewalk and pouring into the streets. We found parking right in front of Brenda's but had to move on because 20 people were hanging out and blocking the spot.

    We ordered:
    Beignet Flight: $9.50 for a sample of four beignets. I'm a fan of the Cajun beignet.
    Pulled Pork Eggs Benedict with choice of hash: the pulled pork was quite good and the hash/country potatoes were surprisingly delicious--they're seasoned very well and are not your typical potatoes.
    Grillades Grits: the gravy had a spicy kick to it.
    Around $37 for the three dishes with tax but pre-tip.

    1 check-in

    I'm going against the majority here to describe my extremely subpar experience at Brenda's. We got here around 9:20 am on a Saturday morning and there was already a long list of names waiting to be seated. I didn't specifically ask for the wait time because I knew I wanted to try this place regardless but a party of 2 that came in shortly after us was told that it would be 15-20 minutes. We were also a party of 2, and we ended up waiting over 40 minutes for a table. They move EXTREMELY SLOW. So many empty tables were open for long periods of time and they wouldn't seat people - I have no idea why. A restaurant as popular as Brenda's should have turnover pretty nailed down at this point but it was painstakingly slow. After 10 am, the wait was looking to be over 2 hours with a huge crowd outside the restaurant.

    The food was really just ok and way over hyped. We tried the beignet flight -  good, but nothing amazing. I've definitely had better beignets. The apple one was most disappointing - both the filling and bread were so dry. Crawfish beignets were unique but I wouldn't come back here just for those. We also got the gumbo which was light and tasty. It has a lot of okra in it so make sure you like okra if you're planning on getting this. The last thing we ordered was the pulled pork benedict special which was a huge mistake. Pulled pork was overly salted to the point where it was almost inedible. The biscuit was crumbly and hard and the hollandaise just added unnecessary creamy cheesiness to an already heavy dish. I rarely send dishes back but I had to tell the waitress that I couldn't eat this at all. She was kind enough to take it off the bill without any issue. I'm adding one star for making that an easy process for me.

    Based on the extremely long wait times and the selection of menu items I've tried, I won't be returning to this spot.

    I have been wanting to try this place forever but there is ALWAYS a long wait, so one Monday when we called around 2pm we were ecstatic to hear that there was NO WAIT at all! It might be a little difficult to find, there is not a huge sign, but it is right next door to the coffee shop that says that they serve food from Brenda's.

    I really wanted to try the benedicts but they only serve those on the weekends for brunch. We opted for the crawfish beignets, jambalaya (special), and BFC (their version of fried chicken). My fiance is a huge fan of crawfish and he thought the crawfish itself was delicious. They were super flavorful, not super spicy. We both agreed the breading for the beignet was a big plain and a bit much, but getting to the inside with the crawfish made it all worth it. It was definitely worth it cause you get three decently sized beignets! The jambalaya was surprisingly not as spicy as other places, which is good for me because I cannot handle spicy. For you spicy lovers out there you made need to add more fire to it. It was solid, definitely something to get again, and it comes with a salad. The BFC is honestly the BEST part of the meal. It was just right amount of crispiness and super moist on the inside. You get two pretty big pieces too, which is perfect for sharing for you to eat all yourself. If you come to Brenda's you MUST get the fried chicken.

    I can't wait to come back to try the benedicts, especially the fried chicken benedicts!

    3 check-ins

    Lend me your ear (ok, eyes) for a second and I'll tell you a tale of one of the top (if not THE top) brunch experiences I've had in San Francisco...

    It was a brisk (what day in SF isn't, really?), Sunday afternoon and three sisters had a hankering for brunch (which is totally the new happy hour). Armed with the Yelp app, and some insider info, they made their way to the Tenderloin. Yes, the TL, as the locals call it. Now, the TL gets a bad rap, but most of it is deserved, however there are some real diamonds in its rough if you're willing to put on your prostitute and druggie repellant and make the trek there.

    Brenda's already had a wait (which is a given since they serve a flight of beignets), among other phenomenal dishes. Instead of wallowing in "why didn't we get up earlier" pity, we walked over to Phillz for a little pre-brunch beverage and snack while we waited. We prob did wait close to an hour but we found a pocket of sunshine to stand in and sipped on our warm beverages so it wasn't completely unbearable.

    They have a specials board outside that makes you drool in anticipation of what will soon be plated in front of you, and on this particular day I had decided on the pulled pork eggs benedict. It was gorgeously designed with a huge, fluffy poached egg with a silky stream of just enough yolk to complement the pulled pork on the creamy biscuit. Seriously, a whopper, and as if that wasn't enough, it came with some killer bfast potatoes/hash. I also ordered a Creole Bloody Mary that wasn't really as exciting as it sounds, but the dish was so spot on that the drink really wouldn't have held a candle to it any way.

    Sadly we didn't order the beignets, as our eyes were bigger than our hunger pains, but that just means a visit to Brenda's will be in my SF future.

    The end.
